Introduction

As a soon-to-be commuter college student, the idea of driving to campus and getting into a traffic accident is slightly terrifying, especially as ongoing construction plagues campus with numerous torn up roads and alternative routes. This may seem silly, however, traffic accidents are more common than you may think.

According to the CDC, from 1981 to 2010, traffic accidents have been the leading cause of unintentional injury deaths in the U.S. From 2011 to 2021, they were still the second leading cause of unintentional injury deaths, only behind poisoning. As a result, traffic accidents are a serious issue and even non-fatal accidents can still cause damage and inconvenience, so any insights about them could be useful.

This motivated us to try to analyze datasets about traffic accidents, which can provide insights into factors contributing to accidents, patterns in accident occurrences, identifying high-risk areas, and ultimately helping to develop strategies for accident prevention and improving road safety.

We initially looked at the dataset "US_Accidents_March23.csv", which we downloaded here. However, this dataset contains a whopping 7.7 million entries, so we decided to limit our scope. First, we limited the entries to those that had accidents occur in Maryland due to our proximity, so results would be more relevant to us. Secondly, we then limited the number of entries to 100,000 since our initial attempts to load in more data led to technical difficulties and we figured 100,000 entries would be sufficient to analyze.

The final dataset, titled "md_100k.csv" can be found here.

Now we can plot the distribution of the temperature at the time of the accidents, grouped by the different severities, of which there are four.

In [ ]:
temp_sev_distributions = [temp_sev_df["Temperature(F)"][temp_sev_df["Severity"] == i + 1] for i in range(4)]

fig, axs = plt.subplots(2, 2, figsize = (10, 10))

  axs[i].set_xlabel("Temperature (F)")
  axs[i].set_ylabel("Number of Accidents")
  axs[i].set_yticklabels(['{:,}'.format(int(x)) for x in axs[i].get_yticks().tolist()])

<ipython-input-10-8cceb7a7e3eb>:12: UserWarning: FixedFormatter should only be used together with FixedLocator
  axs[i].set_yticklabels(['{:,}'.format(int(x)) for x in axs[i].get_yticks().tolist()])

Visually, it looks like the distributions of severities 1 and 4, which are the lowest and highest severities, respectively, are centered around about 70 degrees. On the other hand, it appears the distributions for severities 2 and 3 are bimodal, with peaks around the low 50s and high 70s.

We are interested in whether the means of the distributions are actually significantly different from each other, so to get a more definitive view, we can apply an ANOVA test. An ANOVA test is appropriate here since the distributions appear roughly normal and each sample should be mostly independent.

Thus, assuming an alpha value of 0.05,

Null hypothesis: There is no significant difference between the means of the distributions for each severity level

Alternative hypothesis: There is a significant difference between the means of the distributions for each severity level

In [ ]:
F, p = f_oneway(temp_sev_distributions[0], temp_sev_distributions[1], temp_sev_distributions[2], temp_sev_distributions[3])
p
Out[ ]:
5.188484206118806e-80

Since the obtained p-value is less than 0.05, we reject the null hypothesis and therefore conclude that there is a significant difference between the means of the distributions for each severity level.

It is interesting to observe that the mode visibility for the second most severe accidents (3) is 11 while mode of all other severity is lower. Also interesting that the visibility for the most and least severe accidents is the same (9). It is also interesting that the highest visibility for an accident is of severity 3.

Running the chi-squared test on this would be interesting to see if the visibility has any bearing on the severity of the crash.

Null hypothesis: There is no significant difference between the visibility means for each severity level.

Alternative hypothesis: There is a significant difference between the visibility means for each severity level.

In [ ]:
contingency_table = pd.crosstab(vis_df['Visibility(mi)'], vis_df['Severity'])
ax = contingency_table.plot(kind='bar', figsize=(12, 7))
plt.xscale('linear')
plt.show()
chi2_contingency(contingency_table).pvalue
Out[ ]:
0.014326877931726016

Since the p-value is significantly less that 0.05, we can conclude that there is a significance correlation between visibility and severity of an accident.

Looking at the distribution, you have a better understanding of what counties see more fatal accidents. This can be quite useful in trying to judge what counties are safer to drive in. Minor accidents, though monetarily expensive don't cost a life. Let's run chi-squared test to see if there is a significant correlation between the county and severity. Chi-squared is suitable since we are working with categorical data.

Null hypothesis: There is no significant difference between the county means for each severity level.

Alternative hypothesis: There is a significant difference between the county means for each severity level.

In [ ]:
